In [[broadcasting]], '''puker''' is a [[slang]] term for a person who employs the [[stereotype|stereotypical]] manner of [[speech]] of a [[disc jockey]] or other [[announcer]]. It refers to a highly affected, back-of-the-throat vocalization that, when taken to the point of [[caricature]], is likened to "puking" ([[vomiting]]). It is used by professionals as a humorously derogatory term for lesser talents who seem to be talking the way they think an announcer is "supposed" to sound, instead of projecting their own unique personality.

A familar send-up of this kind of speech would be the "wild and crazy guy" character portrayed by [[Steve Martin]] in his [[stand-up comedy]] act of the late 1970s.

